00:01:45.280 --> 00:01:49.203
with a couple of sort
of preliminary comments.

00:01:50.090 --> 00:01:53.360
Way back when, when I worked for a member

00:01:53.360 --> 00:01:56.640
of the state legislature, one of the most

00:01:56.640 --> 00:02:01.610
organized and informed
groups were the Developmental

00:02:01.610 --> 00:02:04.110
Disabilities Group, and
I was a District Director

00:02:04.110 --> 00:02:06.690
for a state legislator, and they'd come in

00:02:06.690 --> 00:02:10.070
and they'd say, teach
us all about advocacy.

00:02:10.070 --> 00:02:14.030
How do we get some changes
because at that time,

00:02:14.030 --> 00:02:17.580
not unlike now, state
budget was in trouble

00:02:17.580 --> 00:02:21.380
and there were threats
to funding programs.

00:02:21.380 --> 00:02:24.560
So I've always found the
developmentally disabled

00:02:24.560 --> 00:02:27.450
community willing to step up to the plate,

00:02:27.450 --> 00:02:30.820
tell their stories, share it and say

00:02:30.820 --> 00:02:32.271
this is important to us.

00:02:32.271 --> 00:02:35.773
You need to talk to us, you know we vote.

00:02:37.837 --> 00:02:42.310
And if I were writing this,
I would put it in bold.

00:02:42.310 --> 00:02:44.950
I'd highlight it and I'd underline it.

00:02:44.950 --> 00:02:47.833
We vote, it makes a difference.

00:02:48.830 --> 00:02:53.170
The other preliminary
comment is it's always

00:02:53.170 --> 00:02:55.000
very discouraging to me when I'm talking

00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:57.393
to somebody in Washington DC especially,

00:02:58.650 --> 00:03:00.240
and they're an elected
official or they work

00:03:00.240 --> 00:03:03.980
for an elected official
and they confuse the terms

00:03:03.980 --> 00:03:05.953
Medicare and Medicaid.

00:03:08.190 --> 00:03:10.100
And it happens way more than it should

00:03:10.100 --> 00:03:12.460
since it shouldn't happen at all.

00:03:12.460 --> 00:03:17.460
The key is Medicare is funded by all of us

00:03:17.680 --> 00:03:20.720
who work, through payroll taxes.

00:03:20.720 --> 00:03:24.083
Medicaid comes from the general fund.

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:30.000
And it is not only the
safety net for folks

00:03:30.060 --> 00:03:33.320
who are low income, but
it is the safety net

00:03:33.320 --> 00:03:37.682
for anyone who has high
medical bills with the idea

00:03:37.682 --> 00:03:42.480
that you don't go broke
because of high medical costs.

00:03:42.480 --> 00:03:46.493
So part of my job is stereotype breaking.

00:03:48.660 --> 00:03:51.230
I won't let people get away with saying

00:03:51.230 --> 00:03:53.390
oh those poor people,
they're just on welfare

00:03:53.390 --> 00:03:55.440
and they don't do anything to deserve it.

00:03:55.440 --> 00:03:57.240
That's baloney.

00:03:57.240 --> 00:04:00.710
And part of what we
have to do is put a face

00:04:00.710 --> 00:04:05.570
on who's on Medicaid or
in California, MediCal.

00:04:05.570 --> 00:04:10.570
The one other point I would
make is that the formula,

00:04:13.280 --> 00:04:15.370
Amy went through and talked
to you about the formula

00:04:15.370 --> 00:04:19.390
and the FMAP, it's an antiquated formula.

00:04:19.390 --> 00:04:20.643
But we can't change it.

00:04:21.980 --> 00:04:23.770
It's antiquated because it's based

00:04:23.770 --> 00:04:27.240
on both the state's poverty level

00:04:27.240 --> 00:04:29.360
and a per capita.

00:04:29.360 --> 00:04:31.384
Well California has one of the highest

00:04:31.384 --> 00:04:33.730
poverty rates in the country.

00:04:33.730 --> 00:04:35.610
So you would think that our rate would be

00:04:35.610 --> 00:04:37.170
so much higher.

00:04:37.170 --> 00:04:40.230
Well we have a little
problem in that we've got

00:04:41.382 --> 00:04:42.623
the Bay area.

00:04:43.870 --> 00:04:45.740
More specifically we've got Silicon Valley

00:04:45.740 --> 00:04:50.350
and San Francisco, drives
up the per capita income

00:04:50.350 --> 00:04:52.140
for the entire state.

00:04:52.140 --> 00:04:55.120
So while we have one of
the highest poverty rates,

00:04:55.120 --> 00:04:57.490
we also have the highest per capita,

00:04:57.490 --> 00:05:00.680
which keeps us at that 50%.

00:05:00.680 --> 00:05:03.750
It's problematic but we're never gonna get

00:05:03.750 --> 00:05:05.530
that changed unfortunately
because there are

00:05:05.530 --> 00:05:09.133
more states than us and
they have the votes.

00:05:10.140 --> 00:05:12.020
The other big difference between Medicare

00:05:12.020 --> 00:05:15.020
and Medicaid and it comes
in here, is that Medicare

00:05:15.020 --> 00:05:20.020
is a federal program that
says here are all the things

00:05:20.880 --> 00:05:22.290
you have to do.

00:05:22.290 --> 00:05:25.520
It may be implemented on
a state-by-state basis

00:05:25.520 --> 00:05:29.610
or a region, but there are
clear federal guidelines.

00:05:29.610 --> 00:05:31.360
It is a federal program.

00:05:31.360 --> 00:05:35.030
Medicaid has a federal umbrella who says

00:05:35.030 --> 00:05:38.050
you have to do these kinds of things

00:05:38.050 --> 00:05:42.127
but beyond that, you can do what you want

00:05:42.127 --> 00:05:46.710
and it's really, thank
you, as I lose my voice.

00:05:46.710 --> 00:05:48.410
Which is probably not a bad thing.

00:05:51.520 --> 00:05:55.310
There are 54 different Medicaid programs

00:05:55.310 --> 00:05:56.770
in the country.

00:05:56.770 --> 00:06:00.370
One Medicare program,
54 Medicaid programs.

00:06:00.370 --> 00:06:02.250
It makes a huge difference
when you're trying

00:06:02.250 --> 00:06:04.530
to advocate, when you're
trying to make changes,

00:06:04.530 --> 00:06:07.853
when you're trying to protect the program.

00:06:10.460 --> 00:06:13.733
But neither Lisa or I
have anything to disclose.

00:06:14.610 --> 00:06:17.250
And so I wanna talk more deeply about

00:06:18.510 --> 00:06:20.020
who are the children that are covered

00:06:20.020 --> 00:06:21.570
by Medicare and CHIP?

00:06:21.570 --> 00:06:24.460
CHIP stands for the Children's
Health Insurance Program

00:06:24.460 --> 00:06:27.720
and when congress first
passed CHIP they said,

00:06:27.720 --> 00:06:29.430
okay, we've taken care of kids.

00:06:29.430 --> 00:06:31.140
We don't have to worry about that anymore.

00:06:31.140 --> 00:06:32.003
Let's move on.

00:06:33.520 --> 00:06:34.783
Mm, not quite true.

00:06:36.710 --> 00:06:40.580
Almost half of the children
with special healthcare needs

00:06:40.580 --> 00:06:43.440
are covered by either Medicare and CHIP

00:06:43.440 --> 00:06:48.440
and in 2008, the last
recession with a big R

00:06:52.430 --> 00:06:55.970
in California, we
combined the CHIP program

00:06:55.970 --> 00:06:58.010
into the MediCal program.

00:06:58.010 --> 00:07:01.040
So even within our MediCal
program in California,

00:07:01.040 --> 00:07:03.800
we have two different FMAPs.

00:07:03.800 --> 00:07:08.693
Because the kids on CHIP,
it's a 65-35% match.

00:07:09.830 --> 00:07:12.825
So the federal government
pays 65% of the cost.

00:07:12.825 --> 00:07:15.400
The state pays 35%.

00:07:15.400 --> 00:07:17.180
But it's all blended together to create

00:07:17.180 --> 00:07:18.663
our Medicaid program.

00:07:23.700 --> 00:07:28.410
As each day is different,
so the cost or share

00:07:28.410 --> 00:07:32.000
of children with special
healthcare needs can vary

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:35.260
from 23% to 67%.

00:07:35.260 --> 00:07:38.650
You heard Amy say they might
have all the eligibility

00:07:38.650 --> 00:07:41.290
requirements but they cap
how much the funding is

00:07:41.290 --> 00:07:42.400
so that limits.

00:07:42.400 --> 00:07:44.580
I talked to my colleagues
at Texas Children's

00:07:44.580 --> 00:07:47.140
all the time who are
lamenting that the state's

00:07:47.140 --> 00:07:48.810
already run out of money and there's kids

00:07:48.810 --> 00:07:51.740
on waiting lists who are eligible

00:07:51.740 --> 00:07:53.123
but the state has no money.

00:07:55.490 --> 00:08:00.490
75% of Medicaid CHIP children with special

00:08:00.510 --> 00:08:04.580
healthcare needs live
in families below 200%

00:08:04.580 --> 00:08:06.030
of the federal poverty level.

00:08:07.840 --> 00:08:11.150
The federal poverty
level is roughly $16,000

00:08:11.150 --> 00:08:13.060
for a family of three.

00:08:13.060 --> 00:08:17.960
So you're talking about $32,000.

00:08:17.960 --> 00:08:21.440
I don't know that you are
surviving very well anywhere

00:08:21.440 --> 00:08:23.510
in the state of California,
but definitely not

00:08:23.510 --> 00:08:24.473
in the bay area.

00:08:27.230 --> 00:08:28.193
This is Tyler.

00:08:29.370 --> 00:08:32.010
Tyler's one of my advocates.

00:08:32.010 --> 00:08:35.120
I took Tyler back to Washington DC with me

00:08:35.120 --> 00:08:37.480
two years ago when he was four.

00:08:37.480 --> 00:08:40.070
He's now six.

00:08:40.070 --> 00:08:43.560
And when I called mom,
'cause I actually have

00:08:43.560 --> 00:08:45.484
written permission and I called mom to say

00:08:45.484 --> 00:08:48.790
is it okay if, I'm doing this conference,

00:08:48.790 --> 00:08:52.100
I wanna show the pictures
from DC and with Tyler

00:08:52.100 --> 00:08:53.370
and show his care map, which you'll see

00:08:53.370 --> 00:08:54.240
in a little bit.

00:08:54.240 --> 00:08:56.870
She said here, let me give
you his updated photo.

00:08:56.870 --> 00:08:59.283
So I think it's okay for
me to talk about Tyler.

00:09:00.760 --> 00:09:05.123
Tyler was born with half a heart.

00:09:06.610 --> 00:09:11.260
And his parents were told he
had, they had two options.

00:09:11.260 --> 00:09:12.980
They could bring him home.

00:09:12.980 --> 00:09:14.976
He was 32 hours old at this point,

00:09:14.976 --> 00:09:17.190
and they could bring
him home and say goodbye

00:09:17.190 --> 00:09:20.195
or they could have him
airlifted to Packard.

00:09:20.195 --> 00:09:24.680
Now this is a family
that plans everything.

00:09:24.680 --> 00:09:26.726
They dated for a long time and say okay,

00:09:26.726 --> 00:09:28.970
we've saved up money, we can get married.

00:09:28.970 --> 00:09:29.803
They got married.

00:09:29.803 --> 00:09:32.080
Saved up money said okay,
we could buy our house.

00:09:32.080 --> 00:09:33.100
They bought their house.

00:09:33.100 --> 00:09:35.481
Saved up money and said okay,
we could start our family,

00:09:35.481 --> 00:09:36.910
started our family.

00:09:36.910 --> 00:09:38.450
And they did something
that most of us don't

00:09:38.450 --> 00:09:39.520
even think about.

00:09:39.520 --> 00:09:43.358
They bought helicopter
insurance, life flight insurance

00:09:43.358 --> 00:09:44.690
in their health plan.

00:09:44.690 --> 00:09:47.040
'Cause you know, just never know.

00:09:47.040 --> 00:09:49.540
(laughter)

00:09:49.540 --> 00:09:54.540
And then mom went into labor prematurely.

00:09:55.010 --> 00:09:57.950
Tyler was born, that was their option.

00:09:57.950 --> 00:10:01.480
They said life flight him to Packard.

00:10:01.480 --> 00:10:03.960
He got to Packard before,
well mom was still

00:10:03.960 --> 00:10:07.160
in the hospital, before dad got there.

00:10:07.160 --> 00:10:12.090
He was already into surgery
before dad even got there.

00:10:12.090 --> 00:10:15.080
Turns out though their
helicopter insurance

00:10:15.080 --> 00:10:19.030
was for the wrong helicopter company.

00:10:19.030 --> 00:10:20.823
And so it didn't cover.

00:10:22.653 --> 00:10:26.780
But we take care of things like that.

00:10:26.780 --> 00:10:28.610
It's one of the things
that children's hospitals

00:10:28.610 --> 00:10:29.730
tend to do.

00:10:29.730 --> 00:10:32.440
And we don't want families
to go broke either.

00:10:32.440 --> 00:10:35.090
And so we actually, through
our financial counseling,

00:10:35.090 --> 00:10:36.017
took care of it.

00:10:36.017 --> 00:10:38.310
And I have to tell you
this family also has

00:10:39.150 --> 00:10:41.970
primary health insurance
through dad's job,

00:10:41.970 --> 00:10:45.090
secondary health insurance
through mom's job

00:10:45.090 --> 00:10:49.320
and Medicaid to cover all
of the ancillary services

00:10:49.320 --> 00:10:50.830
and wrap around services.

00:10:50.830 --> 00:10:53.330
They could not survive without that.

00:10:53.330 --> 00:10:56.300
Dad makes choices about where he works

00:10:56.300 --> 00:10:59.630
because of the health insurance.

00:10:59.630 --> 00:11:02.430
So he makes the commute from Scotts Valley

00:11:02.430 --> 00:11:05.300
to San Jose every day
in order to make sure

00:11:05.300 --> 00:11:07.903
that Tyler gets the
coverage that Tyler needs.

00:11:08.940 --> 00:11:11.962
For me, that's a red
flag, something we need

00:11:11.962 --> 00:11:14.080
to do something about.

00:11:14.080 --> 00:11:15.130
That's not okay.

00:11:15.130 --> 00:11:18.690
They should be just able to
focus on doing the right thing

00:11:18.690 --> 00:11:21.340
for their family and
having dad working closer

00:11:21.340 --> 00:11:22.840
to home would sure help a lot.

00:11:26.860 --> 00:11:29.080
So what are the demographics?

00:11:29.080 --> 00:11:31.630
Who are the kids who
are on Medicaid or CHIP

00:11:31.630 --> 00:11:33.403
and have special healthcare needs?

00:11:34.530 --> 00:11:39.530
Well, 7% of them have
incomes that are 400%

00:11:41.950 --> 00:11:43.473
of the federal poverty level.

00:11:44.930 --> 00:11:48.423
This is throughout the US,
so it's not just California.

00:11:49.260 --> 00:11:53.838
43% are less than 100% of
the federal poverty level.

00:11:53.838 --> 00:11:58.260
As any of you who work
with or are somebody

00:11:58.260 --> 00:12:00.870
with a developmental disability, you know

00:12:00.870 --> 00:12:04.020
that it's hard to hold
down a full-time job

00:12:04.020 --> 00:12:07.780
even when you want to,
whether you're a caretaker,

00:12:07.780 --> 00:12:11.550
caregiver, it's just tough to do that.

00:12:11.550 --> 00:12:13.130
And we don't make it any easier.

00:12:13.130 --> 00:12:15.300
So it's really important that we continue

00:12:15.300 --> 00:12:18.380
to be able to provide Medicaid
so that at least families

00:12:18.380 --> 00:12:20.283
know that they have health coverage.

00:12:22.010 --> 00:12:27.010
Their race, ethnicity, 40%
are non-Hispanic white.

00:12:28.770 --> 00:12:30.703
29% are Hispanic.

00:12:31.700 --> 00:12:35.850
22% are non-Hispanic African American.

00:12:35.850 --> 00:12:39.540
So if you start looking
at how our population

00:12:39.540 --> 00:12:43.020
in the country breaks down,
this is pretty similar.

00:12:43.020 --> 00:12:46.410
So again, we're gonna bust a stereotype.

00:12:46.410 --> 00:12:49.653
It's not all people of color.

00:12:50.870 --> 00:12:52.160
It is everyone.

00:12:52.160 --> 00:12:54.713
It can hit anyone's family.

00:12:56.850 --> 00:12:59.860
Now we're gonna start
seeing this age change.

00:12:59.860 --> 00:13:02.320
It used to be you had a lot higher numbers

00:13:02.320 --> 00:13:04.490
of the zero to five, higher percentages,

00:13:04.490 --> 00:13:07.890
and then as they got
older, they got smaller

00:13:07.890 --> 00:13:09.260
the percentages.

00:13:09.260 --> 00:13:12.680
Well one of the good things
is that through medical

00:13:12.680 --> 00:13:17.160
research and technology,
we're saving, not only

00:13:17.160 --> 00:13:20.490
are we saving a lot of
children and families,

00:13:20.490 --> 00:13:23.230
but we're giving them a quality of life.

00:13:23.230 --> 00:13:26.880
Because we often hear, oh
well there's an ethical issue.

00:13:26.880 --> 00:13:28.340
You know you're saving these children

00:13:28.340 --> 00:13:31.300
but now there's this huge cost to society

00:13:31.300 --> 00:13:33.380
for taking care of them.

00:13:33.380 --> 00:13:35.948
Well guess what, when we
save children's lives,

00:13:35.948 --> 00:13:38.320
when we give them a productive life,

00:13:38.320 --> 00:13:41.840
they give back and we get those back

00:13:41.840 --> 00:13:45.240
in all sorts of ways.

00:13:45.240 --> 00:13:47.310
So it's a good thing to be doing,

00:13:47.310 --> 00:13:49.593
but it changes our age breakdown.

00:13:52.480 --> 00:13:55.560
The other myth is, oh,
all this money's going

00:13:55.560 --> 00:13:57.360
to all these kids.

00:13:57.360 --> 00:14:01.300
Two-thirds of Medicaid
spending is for elderly

00:14:01.300 --> 00:14:03.210
and then people with disabilities.

00:14:03.210 --> 00:14:07.320
And a lot of the elderly
who have disabilities

00:14:07.320 --> 00:14:09.510
and if they're low income, they qualify.

00:14:09.510 --> 00:14:12.320
You hear them referred to as medi medi's.

00:14:12.320 --> 00:14:16.090
They have Medicare and Medicaid.

00:14:16.090 --> 00:14:19.600
So Medicaid covers their
premiums and other services

00:14:19.600 --> 00:14:21.513
that are not covered by Medicare.

00:14:23.300 --> 00:14:24.900
It makes a difference.

00:14:26.250 --> 00:14:27.790
Children are 43%.

00:14:27.790 --> 00:14:32.740
We usually add in pregnant
women 'cause they're covered

00:14:32.740 --> 00:14:35.090
if they're low income by Medicaid as well.

00:14:35.090 --> 00:14:38.550
And as a children's
hospital that actually has

00:14:38.550 --> 00:14:40.280
a pretty robust labor and delivery,

00:14:40.280 --> 00:14:42.470
we're as interested in that number.

00:14:42.470 --> 00:14:46.360
So about 50% of the people on Medicaid

00:14:46.360 --> 00:14:48.303
are women and children.

00:14:49.200 --> 00:14:52.110
And most of those children
are healthy children.

00:14:52.110 --> 00:14:55.063
And there's some children in
the disabled bucket as well.

00:14:56.530 --> 00:14:59.030
The expenditures, this
is the one that's key.

00:14:59.030 --> 00:15:02.570
Only 19% of expenditures go to children.

00:15:02.570 --> 00:15:07.570
40% of the Medicaid
expenditures go to folks

00:15:08.020 --> 00:15:09.333
who are disabled.

00:15:12.900 --> 00:15:14.900
So what does Medicaid mean for children?

00:15:17.189 --> 00:15:20.820
Medicaid and CHIP, it
benefits the entire family,

00:15:20.820 --> 00:15:22.723
not just the child.

00:15:23.590 --> 00:15:26.170
It provides access to care.

00:15:26.170 --> 00:15:29.160
They're cost-effective programs.

00:15:29.160 --> 00:15:31.990
When children are healthy,
they're less likely

00:15:31.990 --> 00:15:33.490
to miss school.

00:15:33.490 --> 00:15:35.570
They're healthier into adulthood.

00:15:35.570 --> 00:15:37.860
They can earn higher wages.

00:15:37.860 --> 00:15:38.870
And then guess what?

00:15:38.870 --> 00:15:42.233
They can pay more taxes
and keep the cycles going.

00:15:45.620 --> 00:15:47.330
I'm doing a lot of work these days

00:15:47.330 --> 00:15:49.810
on adolescent mental health.

00:15:49.810 --> 00:15:52.110
And I have a lot of frustration
because everybody wants

00:15:52.110 --> 00:15:57.110
to solve the folks who
are mentally ill coming in

00:15:58.570 --> 00:16:02.240
to the emergency rooms, and
I'm like that's important

00:16:02.240 --> 00:16:05.110
but if we would put some money into kids

00:16:05.110 --> 00:16:07.570
and into prevention, we might be able

00:16:07.570 --> 00:16:09.810
to reduce those costs
when they get to adulthood

00:16:09.810 --> 00:16:12.893
because we will have solved the issue.

00:16:14.187 --> 00:16:17.850
And let's put more
dollars into prevention,

00:16:17.850 --> 00:16:20.260
into caring for children and teens,

00:16:20.260 --> 00:16:22.760
whether it's physical
health and mental health

00:16:22.760 --> 00:16:25.930
and please, please, please,
please, let's get rid

00:16:25.930 --> 00:16:27.170
of the silos.

00:16:27.170 --> 00:16:30.340
Let's encourage integrated healthcare.

00:16:30.340 --> 00:16:31.853
It's better for everyone.

00:16:35.220 --> 00:16:37.660
Medicaid enables low-income
children to receive

00:16:37.660 --> 00:16:42.020
that needed care without co
payments and deductibles.

00:16:42.020 --> 00:16:44.360
I often hear people say, and legislators

00:16:44.360 --> 00:16:47.870
or legislative staff saying
well if people would buy

00:16:47.870 --> 00:16:50.300
into the system, you know a co-pay, $50,

00:16:50.300 --> 00:16:51.683
it's no big deal.

00:16:54.390 --> 00:16:59.158
I wanted to ask them if they
would spend a week living

00:16:59.158 --> 00:17:02.320
either as someone with a disability

00:17:02.320 --> 00:17:05.460
or on a limited budget that
would qualify for Medicaid

00:17:05.460 --> 00:17:08.943
and then tell me that $50 is no big deal.

00:17:09.960 --> 00:17:12.115
I want them to have to make that decision.

00:17:12.115 --> 00:17:16.410
I have $50, my kid's healthy
this week, this month.

00:17:16.410 --> 00:17:19.360
Do I pay for a health
premium that we don't need?

00:17:19.360 --> 00:17:21.730
Do I make a rent payment or do I buy food

00:17:21.730 --> 00:17:23.240
for my kids?

00:17:23.240 --> 00:17:25.590
I could tell you which
one comes out on bottom.

00:17:26.630 --> 00:17:29.053
It's an inexpensive way to cover children.

00:17:29.900 --> 00:17:32.410
And when parents are
covered, which is what

00:17:32.410 --> 00:17:35.520
the Affordable Care Act allowed us to do,

00:17:35.520 --> 00:17:37.530
children are more likely to receive

00:17:37.530 --> 00:17:39.640
the preventative healthcare.

00:17:39.640 --> 00:17:42.480
Because parents and kids
are doing this together.

00:17:42.480 --> 00:17:46.490
And it increases access to prenatal care

00:17:46.490 --> 00:17:49.290
which reduces infant
mortality and morbidity

00:17:49.290 --> 00:17:52.730
and we saw it with the passage

00:17:52.730 --> 00:17:55.430
of the Affordable Care
Act for three years,

00:17:55.430 --> 00:17:59.893
from 2014 til last year, we
were seeing those numbers.

00:18:01.550 --> 00:18:04.150
And then as Lisa knows,
Dr. Chamberlain knows,

00:18:04.150 --> 00:18:09.130
my favorite sentence is
Medicaid is the underpinning

00:18:09.130 --> 00:18:11.913
of the entire healthcare
system for children.

00:18:13.930 --> 00:18:15.280
And I wanna repeat that.

00:18:15.280 --> 00:18:18.190
Medicaid is the underpinning
for the entire healthcare

00:18:18.190 --> 00:18:19.490
system for children.

00:18:19.490 --> 00:18:24.180
That means (laughs) thanks Lucy.

00:18:24.180 --> 00:18:26.873
See, she's always being a caregiver.

00:18:28.526 --> 00:18:32.020
I don't care how much money you make,

00:18:32.020 --> 00:18:35.210
how good your health insurance is,

00:18:35.210 --> 00:18:38.300
if your children's
hospital, whether it's part

00:18:38.300 --> 00:18:41.100
of a large system like the UCs or part

00:18:41.100 --> 00:18:44.000
of a independent non-profit like Packard,

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:47.840
if we haven't been able to
hire the right specialist,

00:18:47.840 --> 00:18:50.249
one because they are few and far between,

00:18:50.249 --> 00:18:52.330
or two because we don't have enough volume

00:18:52.330 --> 00:18:55.000
to guarantee that they have an expertise,

00:18:55.000 --> 00:18:58.390
not only is that care
not there for a child

00:18:58.390 --> 00:19:02.470
on Medicaid, that care
isn't there for any child.

00:19:02.470 --> 00:19:05.713
So to have a healthy
children's health system,

00:19:06.740 --> 00:19:07.893
you need Medicaid.

00:19:09.160 --> 00:19:12.120
Volume equals expertise.

00:19:12.120 --> 00:19:16.240
There is a reason why, and
I hope that anybody here

00:19:16.240 --> 00:19:18.930
at UCSF doesn't take offense,
but there is a reason

00:19:18.930 --> 00:19:21.500
why Packard is the number one
pediatric transplant program

00:19:21.500 --> 00:19:22.670
in the country.

00:19:22.670 --> 00:19:24.720
It's because it's able to have the volume

00:19:24.720 --> 00:19:28.380
and it takes care of children on Medicaid

00:19:28.380 --> 00:19:30.223
from multiple states.

00:19:33.290 --> 00:19:36.930
What Medicaid means for
children's hospitals is

00:19:36.930 --> 00:19:40.340
that children's hospitals by in large see

00:19:40.340 --> 00:19:42.810
more Medicaid patients
that the vast majority

00:19:42.810 --> 00:19:44.490
of other hospitals.

00:19:44.490 --> 00:19:46.677
Your first response is gonna say, oh,

00:19:47.650 --> 00:19:48.690
I don't think so Sherri.

00:19:48.690 --> 00:19:50.150
What about those public hospitals?

00:19:50.150 --> 00:19:52.100
You've got public hospitals
all through the state.

00:19:52.100 --> 00:19:54.800
They take care of low-income children

00:19:54.800 --> 00:19:56.930
and they take care of Medicaid.

00:19:56.930 --> 00:19:58.150
You're right, they do.

00:19:58.150 --> 00:19:59.720
And they take care of Medicare,

00:19:59.720 --> 00:20:02.060
and they take care of uninsured.

00:20:02.060 --> 00:20:03.370
And when you look at the percentage

00:20:03.370 --> 00:20:07.397
of Medicaid, it's actually
higher in children's hospitals.

00:20:07.397 --> 00:20:09.513
Because we don't take care of Medicare.

00:20:11.040 --> 00:20:13.460
So Packard is on the low end.

00:20:13.460 --> 00:20:16.023
We're only 43% Medicaid.

00:20:17.470 --> 00:20:20.230
Children's Hospital
Los Angeles is hovering

00:20:20.230 --> 00:20:24.860
between 75 and 80% as is
Children's Hospital Oakland

00:20:24.860 --> 00:20:27.713
or now as it's known UCSF Benioff Oakland.

00:20:28.720 --> 00:20:31.173
Valley Children's
Hospital, the same thing.

00:20:32.640 --> 00:20:35.230
So Medicaid is really the foundation

00:20:35.230 --> 00:20:40.230
and when you cut Medicaid,
there isn't anyplace to go.

00:20:45.042 --> 00:20:47.020
And what this does as I said is it allows

00:20:47.020 --> 00:20:50.403
for that much-needed pediatric expertise.

00:20:51.560 --> 00:20:56.310
It's also the foundation
of financial sustainability

00:20:56.310 --> 00:20:57.823
for children's hospitals.

00:20:59.320 --> 00:21:02.010
We depend on those supplemental programs

00:21:02.010 --> 00:21:07.010
what again, if you're a
public hospital is called DSH,

00:21:07.500 --> 00:21:11.990
disproportionate share,
but for private hospitals

00:21:11.990 --> 00:21:14.900
and children's hospitals, it's
called supplemental payment

00:21:14.900 --> 00:21:16.950
or its DSH lookalike.

00:21:16.950 --> 00:21:19.220
It's identical rules to qualify for DSH.

00:21:19.220 --> 00:21:22.750
It's just not called DSH
because of funding streams

00:21:22.750 --> 00:21:26.010
which is all back of the room.

00:21:26.010 --> 00:21:29.610
Graduate medical education,
the provider fee.

00:21:29.610 --> 00:21:32.440
Sometimes adult hospitals get really upset

00:21:32.440 --> 00:21:35.015
because children's hospitals
get the biggest proportion

00:21:35.015 --> 00:21:37.563
of the provider fee in
the state of California.

00:21:38.770 --> 00:21:40.270
Well there are two reasons.

00:21:40.270 --> 00:21:43.640
We have the most beds covered by Medicaid

00:21:43.640 --> 00:21:46.440
and we hay the highest provider taxes.

00:21:46.440 --> 00:21:50.560
So the formula is, you get back based

00:21:50.560 --> 00:21:53.810
on how many MediCal patients you serve

00:21:53.810 --> 00:21:56.543
and what the utilization is.

00:21:58.450 --> 00:22:03.450
I can tell you for Packard,
that's about $65 million

00:22:04.040 --> 00:22:06.000
a year, the provider fee.

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:08.700
We don't qualify for DSH.

00:22:08.700 --> 00:22:13.130
We're in the absolute worst
place you could possibly be.

00:22:13.130 --> 00:22:17.030
We missed qualifying by about 1%.

00:22:17.030 --> 00:22:20.253
Missing by 1% costs us $10 million.

00:22:22.912 --> 00:22:24.963
But it is what it is.

00:22:26.140 --> 00:22:29.080
So we are very dependent and appreciative

00:22:29.080 --> 00:22:30.363
of the provider fee.

00:22:31.670 --> 00:22:34.608
Some of my colleagues are
at children's hospitals

00:22:34.608 --> 00:22:38.950
where they're receiving
hundreds of millions of dollars

00:22:38.950 --> 00:22:40.880
and it literally is the
only way they're able

00:22:40.880 --> 00:22:43.230
to keep programs operating.

00:22:43.230 --> 00:22:45.020
And people say, well but it's a tax.

00:22:45.020 --> 00:22:46.513
So we should cut all taxes.

00:22:47.590 --> 00:22:52.590
This is a tax that we, I'm not
sure gladly is the right term

00:22:52.610 --> 00:22:57.610
but we gladly pay ourselves
and have voted ourselves

00:22:58.780 --> 00:23:01.170
to self tax ourselves in order to be able

00:23:01.170 --> 00:23:05.040
to draw down these federal
dollars because these are dollars

00:23:05.040 --> 00:23:08.630
that the state of California
was leaving on the table.

00:23:08.630 --> 00:23:11.520
California was eligible
for these dollars based

00:23:11.520 --> 00:23:13.740
on the federal government's formula,

00:23:13.740 --> 00:23:16.590
but there wasn't enough money
in the state general fund

00:23:16.590 --> 00:23:18.580
to be able to draw the dollars down.

00:23:18.580 --> 00:23:21.233
So by taxing ourselves as hospitals,

00:23:21.233 --> 00:23:24.310
we give that money to the state to be able

00:23:24.310 --> 00:23:27.910
to bring those dollars down
from the federal government.

00:23:27.910 --> 00:23:32.520
So don't let anyone tell you
that California is getting

00:23:32.520 --> 00:23:34.090
more than its fair share.

00:23:34.090 --> 00:23:37.690
It's not, and California even with this,

00:23:37.690 --> 00:23:40.623
is still a donor state to
the federal government.

