00:27:21.310 --> 00:27:25.570
As a resident, I was so
overwhelmed with I saw

00:27:25.570 --> 00:27:28.002
taking care of these kids and frustrated

00:27:28.002 --> 00:27:31.410
that I couldn't get kids
that I cared for eyeglasses.

00:27:31.410 --> 00:27:33.480
It was actually a 17-year-old girl

00:27:33.480 --> 00:27:35.160
who I'd taken care of for a long time,

00:27:35.160 --> 00:27:39.420
a real bright, bilingual,
bi cultural immigrant girl

00:27:39.420 --> 00:27:41.530
who came to my clinic with headaches,

00:27:41.530 --> 00:27:45.410
and headaches that were
worse at the end of the day.

00:27:45.410 --> 00:27:47.750
This is a kid who had straight As.

00:27:47.750 --> 00:27:48.690
She was awesome.

00:27:48.690 --> 00:27:52.420
And headaches at the ends of
the day, probably squinting.

00:27:52.420 --> 00:27:53.900
That's the first thing
you do, check her vision.

00:27:53.900 --> 00:27:55.530
Sure enough, she needs glasses.

00:27:55.530 --> 00:27:58.410
And this was the day before
the Healthy Kids Program,

00:27:58.410 --> 00:28:01.170
and I could not get her glasses.

00:28:01.170 --> 00:28:03.520
That's what she needed,
a pair of eyeglasses.

00:28:03.520 --> 00:28:05.840
I spent months trying to figure out.

00:28:05.840 --> 00:28:10.160
Because all she had was
EPSDT which meant she

00:28:10.160 --> 00:28:13.290
could be seen on intervals to be cared for

00:28:13.290 --> 00:28:15.080
but she was out of interval.

00:28:15.080 --> 00:28:17.300
And I called the Lion's Club,
and they had a waiting list,

00:28:17.300 --> 00:28:21.540
and I spent my own time
calling different providers.

00:28:21.540 --> 00:28:23.950
I finally found someone in Burlingame.

00:28:23.950 --> 00:28:25.210
And I remember the day I called her.

00:28:25.210 --> 00:28:26.350
I was so excited.

00:28:26.350 --> 00:28:28.790
I found an optometrist
that's gonna get you glasses.

00:28:28.790 --> 00:28:31.710
And she was like, oh okay, where is it?

00:28:31.710 --> 00:28:33.020
I said, Burlingame.

00:28:33.020 --> 00:28:36.543
And she said, oh, how will
I ever get to Burlingame,

00:28:37.990 --> 00:28:40.880
'cause she was down with
us in East Palo Alto.

00:28:40.880 --> 00:28:45.360
And I just remember, so
overwhelmed and feeling

00:28:45.360 --> 00:28:47.500
like how can I practice medicine.

00:28:47.500 --> 00:28:48.840
How can I do this?

00:28:48.840 --> 00:28:50.880
I know I'm drawn to care
for underserved patients

00:28:50.880 --> 00:28:53.460
but how can I do this and
not completely burn out.

00:28:53.460 --> 00:28:57.257
Because as physicians we
inherit failed social policy.

00:28:57.257 --> 00:28:59.230
It was a failed social policy that put me

00:28:59.230 --> 00:29:00.940
in that situation.

00:29:00.940 --> 00:29:03.450
And there was no way I
could sustainably practice

00:29:03.450 --> 00:29:05.720
and care for this
population unless I started

00:29:05.720 --> 00:29:08.400
to figure out how to change these policies

00:29:08.400 --> 00:29:09.730
and get activated around that.

00:29:09.730 --> 00:29:11.740
And that's been a bit part of my career

00:29:11.740 --> 00:29:14.344
and what I'm gonna talk to
about in our last 15 minutes

00:29:14.344 --> 00:29:15.933
for this session.

