00:29:42.370 --> 00:29:43.909
that create the problems.

00:29:43.909 --> 00:29:46.620
So I'm not gonna show you any statistics.

00:29:46.620 --> 00:29:48.230
Like I've learned a lot just listening

00:29:48.230 --> 00:29:51.100
and I thought I knew a lot about Medicaid,

00:29:51.100 --> 00:29:53.860
but I'm gonna tell stories
about how we are working

00:29:53.860 --> 00:29:55.870
in pediatrics and how I hope we can start

00:29:55.870 --> 00:29:58.770
creating trans disciplinary
action together

00:29:58.770 --> 00:30:01.523
with other fields to improve
the health of children.

00:30:02.970 --> 00:30:06.360
So the story I wanna tell
first is what happened

00:30:06.360 --> 00:30:08.460
in the fall of 2016.

00:30:08.460 --> 00:30:10.930
So we'd come through
an interesting election

00:30:10.930 --> 00:30:13.100
and we're hit with a series of headlines

00:30:13.100 --> 00:30:16.570
that threatened a lot
of what we care about,

00:30:16.570 --> 00:30:19.790
headlines around repealing the ACA

00:30:19.790 --> 00:30:23.180
and changes around immigration policy.

00:30:23.180 --> 00:30:26.510
And the pediatric residents
that I work with at Stanford

00:30:26.510 --> 00:30:28.740
came to me an said we are really worried

00:30:28.740 --> 00:30:29.940
about our families.

00:30:29.940 --> 00:30:32.240
We are hearing from our
families that they are scared,

00:30:32.240 --> 00:30:33.700
that they don't want to come to clinic,

00:30:33.700 --> 00:30:36.670
that they're gonna lose
their healthcare coverage.

00:30:36.670 --> 00:30:37.890
What could we do about this?

00:30:37.890 --> 00:30:39.980
And part of my job there is to talk about

00:30:39.980 --> 00:30:41.210
the social determinants of health

00:30:41.210 --> 00:30:42.630
and to teach them about health policy.

00:30:42.630 --> 00:30:45.060
And so I said well, I
don't know, let's think.

00:30:45.060 --> 00:30:46.430
Let's throw it open.

00:30:46.430 --> 00:30:47.550
We got to talk to Sherri.

00:30:47.550 --> 00:30:50.080
So that's my first call all the time.

00:30:50.080 --> 00:30:52.149
And she said well why
don't we have a town hall.

00:30:52.149 --> 00:30:54.760
So we opened up a town hall and not just

00:30:54.760 --> 00:30:59.050
to our physicians at
Packard but to all staff.

00:30:59.050 --> 00:31:01.400
Emails went out to everyone
saying if you're concerned

00:31:01.400 --> 00:31:05.430
about the changing kind
of prevailing wisdom

00:31:05.430 --> 00:31:08.020
coming from the east coast
right now, come talk to us.

00:31:08.020 --> 00:31:10.410
And so we held a town hall, and had three

00:31:10.410 --> 00:31:13.340
quick presentations on the
changes around Medicaid,

00:31:13.340 --> 00:31:14.850
around immigration and about funding

00:31:14.850 --> 00:31:16.150
for pediatric research.

00:31:16.150 --> 00:31:18.780
And then just opened it up and said what,

00:31:18.780 --> 00:31:21.050
it was a group about this size,
said what do you guys want

00:31:21.050 --> 00:31:21.883
to do about it.

00:31:21.883 --> 00:31:23.780
You're people who came
out on a whatever it was,

00:31:23.780 --> 00:31:25.730
Tuesday night, to talk about this.

00:31:25.730 --> 00:31:26.650
What are you interested in?

00:31:26.650 --> 00:31:29.060
And we brainstormed
together for about an hour.

00:31:29.060 --> 00:31:31.700
And this group of people
said what we want to do

00:31:31.700 --> 00:31:34.110
is have a strong, coherent voice together

00:31:34.110 --> 00:31:36.650
to fight for our families
and to fight for our kids.

00:31:36.650 --> 00:31:39.090
And that was the beginning of what we call

00:31:39.090 --> 00:31:43.310
our Policy Response Team that now exists

00:31:43.310 --> 00:31:45.030
down at Packard.

00:31:45.030 --> 00:31:48.660
And we kinda came together
and had two main goals.

00:31:48.660 --> 00:31:50.930
One was to organize and
strengthen our local

00:31:50.930 --> 00:31:53.190
professional community
so that we could better

00:31:53.190 --> 00:31:56.510
advocate together in a
real time sensitive way

00:31:56.510 --> 00:31:59.260
when different issues came forward.

00:31:59.260 --> 00:32:00.930
And we also wanted to educate ourselves.

00:32:00.930 --> 00:32:02.720
We wanted to educate the next generation

00:32:02.720 --> 00:32:06.240
of pediatricians as well
as everyone around us

00:32:06.240 --> 00:32:09.590
about the important
impact that these things

00:32:09.590 --> 00:32:11.343
were having on our families.

00:32:12.500 --> 00:32:16.130
So over the last year
and a half we've taken

00:32:16.130 --> 00:32:17.490
a lot of action together.

00:32:17.490 --> 00:32:21.500
You can see some signs here
around different issues,

00:32:21.500 --> 00:32:24.420
DACA and CHIP being a couple big ones.

00:32:24.420 --> 00:32:26.880
And the ways we've done that,
a lot of teaching sessions.

00:32:26.880 --> 00:32:30.182
So we went from having a
couple policy updates a year

00:32:30.182 --> 00:32:32.010
to closer to 12.

00:32:32.010 --> 00:32:34.650
So almost every month we're
having a different topic

00:32:34.650 --> 00:32:37.383
and teaching the residents
about these issues.

00:32:38.520 --> 00:32:40.520
And then the importance
of letting, we said,

00:32:40.520 --> 00:32:42.450
go into those town halls.

00:32:42.450 --> 00:32:44.120
Our legislators come home.

00:32:44.120 --> 00:32:46.930
They have town halls,
and we not only have them

00:32:46.930 --> 00:32:49.300
on our calendar, we send
emails out to everyone,

00:32:49.300 --> 00:32:51.010
there's a town hall, who can go.

00:32:51.010 --> 00:32:51.970
Who wants to go together?

00:32:51.970 --> 00:32:54.010
Let's carpool, let's get down there.

00:32:54.010 --> 00:32:56.030
And you can see we wear our white coats.

00:32:56.030 --> 00:32:57.040
We stand up.

00:32:57.040 --> 00:32:58.900
We talk about kids.

00:32:58.900 --> 00:33:00.820
We talk about the
importance of these issues.

00:33:00.820 --> 00:33:03.380
Sometimes when it's Anna Eshoo's town hall

00:33:03.380 --> 00:33:05.130
for instance, we thank her.

00:33:05.130 --> 00:33:07.540
Thank you for being a
champion for children.

00:33:07.540 --> 00:33:08.560
We appreciate that.

00:33:08.560 --> 00:33:13.560
You have to shore up those
who are your champions

00:33:13.790 --> 00:33:16.760
in Washington and who
consistently are a voice

00:33:16.760 --> 00:33:19.113
for the families that we care about.

00:33:20.200 --> 00:33:21.700
And it's interesting, when you stand up

00:33:21.700 --> 00:33:23.877
and talk at these things,
the media follow you out

00:33:23.877 --> 00:33:27.060
and say excuse me, excuse
me, can we get a quote?

00:33:27.060 --> 00:33:30.110
And so our residents
and our faculty have had

00:33:30.110 --> 00:33:33.560
many opportunities to talk and get our

00:33:33.560 --> 00:33:36.240
voice out even further.

00:33:36.240 --> 00:33:38.860
And one thing I've noticed,
I think it can feel

00:33:38.860 --> 00:33:41.210
intimidating to go by yourself.

00:33:41.210 --> 00:33:43.230
This idea of I'm gonna look it up,

00:33:43.230 --> 00:33:44.890
and I'm gonna go and I'm
gonna speak to people.

00:33:44.890 --> 00:33:47.840
But as a group, people seem to love it.

00:33:47.840 --> 00:33:50.380
Like okay, who can go
this Saturday afternoon

00:33:50.380 --> 00:33:51.930
and we'll all go grab
lunch and we'll think

00:33:51.930 --> 00:33:53.180
about what's happening, and then lets

00:33:53.180 --> 00:33:54.320
just all go together.

00:33:54.320 --> 00:33:56.180
And if it's your first one,
you can just sit there.

00:33:56.180 --> 00:33:57.623
You don't have to say anything.

00:33:58.479 --> 00:34:01.840
You know so this idea I
think that we're not alone.

00:34:01.840 --> 00:34:04.410
We're in this together and we really need

00:34:04.410 --> 00:34:06.537
to start getting more organized I think

00:34:06.537 --> 00:34:08.490
in working together with this.

00:34:08.490 --> 00:34:11.020
And we would certainly
welcome our colleagues

00:34:11.020 --> 00:34:14.100
who are again, in different
fields, joining us on these.

00:34:14.100 --> 00:34:17.550
Because I think we can all
tell those powerful stories.

00:34:17.550 --> 00:34:20.450
We are getting very organized
about letter writing.

00:34:20.450 --> 00:34:22.000
We have lots of opportunities.

00:34:22.000 --> 00:34:23.930
Every single teaching
conference that we do

00:34:23.930 --> 00:34:28.784
is accompanied by an opportunity
to send letters, to tweet.

00:34:28.784 --> 00:34:31.030
I'm gonna get to that in a minute.

00:34:31.030 --> 00:34:33.273
To get our voices out,
to make phone calls.

00:34:33.273 --> 00:34:35.530
But the letter writing,
if for instance we have

00:34:35.530 --> 00:34:38.070
a grand rounds that has a policy angle,

00:34:38.070 --> 00:34:43.070
we had one recently on the
increasing price of insulin

00:34:43.600 --> 00:34:46.420
and just how crazy that
is, what's going on.

00:34:46.420 --> 00:34:48.430
And so where there's something that again

00:34:48.430 --> 00:34:51.442
that failed social policy
that we are all inheriting,

00:34:51.442 --> 00:34:54.480
we have out, kind of
like where we signed in

00:34:54.480 --> 00:34:57.050
and got our badges, at
grand rounds we have

00:34:57.050 --> 00:34:57.883
a similar table.

00:34:57.883 --> 00:35:00.830
There are letters out there
to make it easy for you.

00:35:00.830 --> 00:35:01.740
Grab one of these.

00:35:01.740 --> 00:35:03.940
Take it in, write it while
you're sitting in grand rounds.

00:35:03.940 --> 00:35:05.790
Drop it off at the end or do it at the end

00:35:05.790 --> 00:35:07.270
and we'll get that sent for you.

00:35:07.270 --> 00:35:08.910
So just putting it in front of people.

00:35:08.910 --> 00:35:12.670
Operationalizing, we could
have an advocacy letter today,

00:35:12.670 --> 00:35:14.820
right, we could take advantage of the time

00:35:14.820 --> 00:35:17.470
that we're together to
raise our voice together,

00:35:17.470 --> 00:35:19.740
make it easy for people to address

00:35:19.740 --> 00:35:21.283
these policy issues.

00:35:22.530 --> 00:35:24.420
We've coordinated greatly with the

00:35:24.420 --> 00:35:27.120
American Academy of
Pediatrics where Lucy was

00:35:27.120 --> 00:35:29.800
enormous leadership role for many years

00:35:31.090 --> 00:35:33.270
to raise our voice even more broadly

00:35:33.270 --> 00:35:35.513
and to coordinate things nationally.

00:35:36.700 --> 00:35:40.810
So one of our opportunities in California

00:35:40.810 --> 00:35:43.070
and Lucy eluded to it is that years ago

00:35:43.070 --> 00:35:46.850
we built a collaboration
between the 14 training programs

00:35:46.850 --> 00:35:50.710
in California, and I did that with Lucy,

00:35:50.710 --> 00:35:55.059
with Dr. Andequo and
Gina Lewis, both up here,

00:35:55.059 --> 00:35:57.680
and reached out to the
other training programs

00:35:57.680 --> 00:36:00.190
and said hey we really could
have a much more powerful

00:36:00.190 --> 00:36:02.920
voice in Sacramento if
we organized ourselves

00:36:02.920 --> 00:36:07.050
and if we spoke together in
a much more coherent way.

00:36:07.050 --> 00:36:09.300
And so we've reached out
on these American Academy

00:36:09.300 --> 00:36:12.170
of Pediatric days of
action because that kind of

00:36:12.170 --> 00:36:14.700
is an umbrella across all of our campuses.

00:36:14.700 --> 00:36:16.750
We're all parts of the AAP.

00:36:16.750 --> 00:36:19.250
And so we take action when they have days

00:36:19.250 --> 00:36:21.390
to take action together, we make sure

00:36:21.390 --> 00:36:24.829
that every single program in
California is participating,

00:36:24.829 --> 00:36:27.730
and the voice roaring out of California

00:36:27.730 --> 00:36:30.683
has not been small I'm very proud to say.

00:36:32.270 --> 00:36:35.840
And because of all this, I'm
not a social media person

00:36:35.840 --> 00:36:38.082
my daughters will tell you, I'm hopeless.

00:36:38.082 --> 00:36:41.920
But I have joined Twitter.

00:36:41.920 --> 00:36:44.300
And it is a part of my job.

00:36:44.300 --> 00:36:48.130
It is a really important way to advocate.

00:36:48.130 --> 00:36:50.190
And I asked Lucy, I said
what's your Twitter handle

00:36:50.190 --> 00:36:51.350
for this meeting.

00:36:51.350 --> 00:36:54.740
Because I took pictures of
Lucy and Amy standing after.

00:36:54.740 --> 00:36:56.150
I would be tweeting about this.

00:36:56.150 --> 00:36:58.000
And people across the
country who follow me

00:36:58.000 --> 00:36:59.320
would be hearing about this.

00:36:59.320 --> 00:37:01.280
I've wanted to thank
Kaiser for that great slide

00:37:01.280 --> 00:37:02.720
I used, that slide you used all the time.

00:37:02.720 --> 00:37:04.170
I was gonna write, I
already know the tweet

00:37:04.170 --> 00:37:06.950
I'm gonna send, thank you
@Kaiser Family Foundation,

00:37:06.950 --> 00:37:08.670
you know we continue to use your site.

00:37:08.670 --> 00:37:10.153
But Kaiser will see that.

00:37:10.990 --> 00:37:12.870
There's somebody at Kaiser
watching that today,

00:37:12.870 --> 00:37:14.080
their Twitter feed.

00:37:14.080 --> 00:37:16.560
It is a really powerful way,
and this is the very first

00:37:16.560 --> 00:37:18.040
tweet I sent up there on top.

00:37:18.040 --> 00:37:20.650
It says #Firsttweet, so your first tweet

00:37:20.650 --> 00:37:22.073
is always followed.

00:37:22.073 --> 00:37:25.300
But it's interesting because
at the morning conference

00:37:25.300 --> 00:37:26.610
and we were getting the residents ready

00:37:26.610 --> 00:37:29.510
to do this Twitter storm, I said okay,

00:37:29.510 --> 00:37:31.630
everyone get out and log on to Twitter.

00:37:31.630 --> 00:37:33.280
And they all looked at me.

00:37:33.280 --> 00:37:35.578
And I'm like, you are
all on Twitter, right?

00:37:35.578 --> 00:37:37.725
And they're like, no.

00:37:37.725 --> 00:37:38.840
(laughter)

00:37:38.840 --> 00:37:40.838
and I was like oh my, really?

00:37:40.838 --> 00:37:42.497
And they're all on Instagram and Snapchat,

00:37:42.497 --> 00:37:45.323
which I'm aware of because
I have teenage daughters.

00:37:46.183 --> 00:37:49.506
And they're like, Twitter's
like for grown ups.

00:37:49.506 --> 00:37:51.756
(laughter)

00:37:54.181 --> 00:37:56.539
Which explains why I like
it and I'm not on Snapchat

00:37:56.539 --> 00:37:57.706
and Instagram.

00:37:58.759 --> 00:38:01.240
It is actually work.

00:38:01.240 --> 00:38:04.170
The people on Twitter
are having conversations

00:38:04.170 --> 00:38:08.098
about policy, about guns, about taxes.

00:38:08.098 --> 00:38:12.760
It is not social in the same way

00:38:12.760 --> 00:38:14.690
that I had thought of the Facebooks

00:38:14.690 --> 00:38:15.690
and everything else.

00:38:15.690 --> 00:38:18.120
This I really have shifted
in the last six months.

00:38:18.120 --> 00:38:19.800
This is a part of my job.

00:38:19.800 --> 00:38:21.660
It is my job to get it out there.

00:38:21.660 --> 00:38:23.640
It is my job to stay on for it.

00:38:23.640 --> 00:38:26.310
And the people who make decisions listen

00:38:26.310 --> 00:38:28.080
to this conversation.

00:38:28.080 --> 00:38:29.550
And that's why we have to be on it.

00:38:29.550 --> 00:38:31.830
So I would encourage you, maybe set a goal

00:38:31.830 --> 00:38:33.810
to at least talk to someone
about getting on Twitter.

00:38:33.810 --> 00:38:35.210
It's really not hard at all.

00:38:36.540 --> 00:38:37.563
I was surprised.

00:38:39.070 --> 00:38:43.376
So as an example of the power of Twitter,

00:38:43.376 --> 00:38:46.400
the American Academy had
a day of Stand for CHIP

00:38:46.400 --> 00:38:49.000
because we were just so
unbelievably frustrated

00:38:49.000 --> 00:38:50.960
with that situation.

00:38:50.960 --> 00:38:52.230
Took a lot of action that day.

00:38:52.230 --> 00:38:54.420
We had good media coverage,
not just at Packard

00:38:54.420 --> 00:38:55.863
but across the state.

00:38:56.750 --> 00:38:57.630
And here are the numbers.

00:38:57.630 --> 00:38:58.980
We used two different hashtags.

00:38:58.980 --> 00:39:01.350
It's kinda how Twitter
organizes their conversations.

00:39:01.350 --> 00:39:03.193
So one hashtag was #DontCapMyCare.

00:39:04.576 --> 00:39:07.150
It had about 6,000 posts
snatched nationally

00:39:07.150 --> 00:39:09.963
which means we reached four
million individual people.

00:39:10.902 --> 00:39:13.990
#KeepKidsCovered was the
other hashtag we used.

00:39:13.990 --> 00:39:17.520
8,000 posts, almost nine million people.

00:39:17.520 --> 00:39:20.090
And having spent two
years working part time

00:39:20.090 --> 00:39:21.660
in Sacramento 'cause
I wanted to understand

00:39:21.660 --> 00:39:23.770
this policy better, I
can tell you the staffers

00:39:23.770 --> 00:39:26.410
who report directly to the legislators

00:39:26.410 --> 00:39:28.570
sit in front of screens
with the Twitter feed

00:39:28.570 --> 00:39:31.720
over here, and they watch
what's called trending.

00:39:31.720 --> 00:39:32.640
What's trending?

00:39:32.640 --> 00:39:33.660
What's everyone talking about?

00:39:33.660 --> 00:39:34.493
What is this?

00:39:34.493 --> 00:39:35.920
What is this don't cap my care?

00:39:35.920 --> 00:39:37.550
What is this keep kids covered?

00:39:37.550 --> 00:39:39.540
And they will click
through and they will look

00:39:39.540 --> 00:39:40.970
at our conversation.

00:39:40.970 --> 00:39:43.320
So on both on this day when we did this,

00:39:43.320 --> 00:39:45.090
we trended all day long.

00:39:45.090 --> 00:39:48.230
We know we reached every
single staffer on the hill

00:39:48.230 --> 00:39:49.950
with these messages that day.

00:39:49.950 --> 00:39:51.670
And that's why this is important.

00:39:51.670 --> 00:39:52.870
That's why this matters.

00:39:55.040 --> 00:39:57.520
Because of this, because
our residents have just been

00:39:57.520 --> 00:40:00.272
unbelievably inspiring,
Sherri asked if she

00:40:00.272 --> 00:40:02.880
could take them to Washington with her

00:40:02.880 --> 00:40:03.910
on one of her trips.

00:40:03.910 --> 00:40:07.460
There's a couple of them over
here on right, Lee and Jen.

00:40:07.460 --> 00:40:09.620
So they got to go to
Washington, walk the halls

00:40:09.620 --> 00:40:11.700
with Sherri, which is
where I got my education.

00:40:11.700 --> 00:40:15.163
So it was real pleased that
they were able to do that.

00:40:16.360 --> 00:40:18.690
We've also created a story
bank because the power

00:40:18.690 --> 00:40:21.360
of stories is so
important and what this is

00:40:21.360 --> 00:40:25.040
is a secure Google doc in our hospital

00:40:25.040 --> 00:40:28.540
that our residents and
others if they have stories

00:40:28.540 --> 00:40:30.570
if they are feeling
frustrated and they want

00:40:30.570 --> 00:40:32.383
to put their story down they can.

00:40:33.680 --> 00:40:35.527
Here's one somebody put in.

00:40:35.527 --> 00:40:38.297
"A mother of two school-age
children with terrible oral

00:40:38.297 --> 00:40:40.667
"sores was afraid to come to the doctor

00:40:40.667 --> 00:40:42.332
"or the emergency room because she has

00:40:42.332 --> 00:40:45.587
"an electronic bracelet is
worried about getting deported.

00:40:45.587 --> 00:40:47.327
"She was so scared to
come in that by the time

00:40:47.327 --> 00:40:50.730
"they arrived, both children
were severely dehydrated."

